wikipedia_page.main: James Rankine (1828 – 8 September 1897), often referred to as "Captain Rankine", was a farmer, businessman and politician in the early days of the Colony of South Australia.

response: 1849: Dr. John Rankine was granted an occupational licence to become the island's first grazier. His nephew James Rankine was an early and longtime settler.

link_mentions.page: Members of the South Australian House of Assembly, 1865–1868

response: *He was elected to the fourth Parliament, assembled 31 March 1865 with James Rankine. This parliament was dissolved on 26 March 1868 and Dunn was beaten in the election of the fifth Parliament by John Cheriton. On 12 August however a fresh election was called by the Court of Disputed Returns and Dunn was elected along with Cheriton. This did not last long however, as Dunn was accused of paying the travel expenses of some electors, a charge which he vehemently denied, and was unseated.

Members of the South Australian Legislative Council, 1885–1888

response: Rankine (often spelled Rankin) was born in Ayrshire, Scotland, a son of James Rankine and his wife Jane Rankine, née Paterson. He may have visited Van Diemen's Land (now Tasmania) as ship's doctor on the Sir William Bentinck in August 1838.
He was an uncle of fellow South Australian parliamentarian James Rankine.
